<subsection xml:id="subsec-parallel-vectors">
    <title>Parallel Vectors</title>
    <p>
        Vectors that have the same or opposite direction are called <m>{\color{red}\text{parallel vectors.}}</m>
    </p>
    <example>
        <statement>
            <p>
                Identify parallel, equal and opposite vectors from <xref ref="parallel-vectors-1"/> below.
            </p>
            <sidebyside>
                <tabular>
                <row>
                    <cell><m>(a)</m></cell>   
                </row>
            </tabular>
            <tabular>
                <row>
                    <cell><m>(b)</m></cell>
                </row>
            </tabular>
            </sidebyside>
            
            <figure xml:id="parallel-vectors-1">
                <caption></caption>
                <sidebyside widths="70% 30%">
                    <image>
                        <latex-image>
                            \begin{tikzpicture}
                                \usetikzlibrary{arrows.meta}
                                % Draw fine grid (10x smaller squares)
                                %\draw[gray!30, very thin, step=0.1] (-2,-2) grid (10,10);

                                % Draw main grid (original)
                                \draw[gray!70, thin, step=1] (-2,-2) grid (9,9);

                                % Draw axes
                                \draw[red,thick,-&gt;] (-1,0) -- (8,0) node[right,black] {\large $x$};
                                \draw[red,thick,-&gt;] (0,-1) -- (0,8) node[above,black] {\large $y$};


                                % Define points
                                \coordinate (A) at (1,3);
                                \coordinate (B) at (4,6);
                                \node at (0.7,3) {\large $A$};
                                \node[red] at (1.8,1) {\large $C$};
                                \node[blue] at (5.7,3) {\large $E$};
                                \node[blue] at (7.2,4) {\large $F$};
                                \coordinate (C) at (2,1);
                                \coordinate (D) at (4,3);
                                \coordinate (E) at (6,3);
                                \coordinate (F) at (7,4);

                                \draw [-{Latex[scale=2]}] (A) -- (B) ;
                                \draw [-{Latex[scale=2]},red] (D) -- (C) ;
                                \draw [-{Latex[scale=2]},blue] (E) -- (F) ;

                                % Draw vectors
                                \draw[thick] (A) -- (B) node[right] {B};
                                \draw[thick,red] (C) -- (D) node[right] {D}; 
                            \end{tikzpicture}
                        </latex-image>
                    </image>

                    <image>
                        <latex-image>
                            \begin{tikzpicture}
                                \usetikzlibrary{arrows.meta}
   
                                % Define points
                                \coordinate (Q) at (2,1);
                                \coordinate (O) at (7,3);
                                \node at (1.7,1) {\large $Q$};
                                \node[black] at (4.5,2.3) {\large $P$};
                                \node[black] at (0.7,7) {\large $M$};
                                \node[black] at (6.2,4) {\large $G$};
                                \node[black] at (3.8,5.8) {\large $H$};
                                \coordinate (M) at (1,7);
                                \coordinate (G) at (6,4);
                                \coordinate (H) at (3.5,5.5);
                                

                                \draw [-{Latex[scale=2]}] (Q) -- (O) ;
                                \draw [-{Latex[scale=2]}] (O) -- (Q) ;
                                \draw [-{Latex[scale=2]}] (G) -- (M) ;
                                \draw [-{Latex[scale=2]}] (G) -- (H) ;

                                % Draw vectors
                                \draw[thick] (Q) -- (O) node[right] {O};
                            \end{tikzpicture}
                        </latex-image>
                    </image>
                </sidebyside>
            </figure>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p>
                <ol marker="a.">
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            <m>\overrightarrow{AB}</m> and <m>\overrightarrow{EF}</m> are in the same direction, <m>\overrightarrow{DC}</m> is in opposite direction to <m>\overrightarrow{AB}</m> and <m>\overrightarrow{EF}.</m> 
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            Hence, these vectors <m>\overrightarrow{AB},\, \overrightarrow{EF} </m> and <m>\overrightarrow{DC}</m> are parallel to each other.
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            There is no equal and opposite of a vector in the given figure.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            <m>\overrightarrow{PO}</m> and <m>\overrightarrow{PQ}</m> are in opposite directions but on the same line, so they are parallel.
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            Vectors <m>\overrightarrow{GH}</m> and <m>\overrightarrow{GM}</m> are also parallel since they are <m>{\color{red}\text{vectors}}</m> in the same direction.
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            There is no vector which is opposite of another in the given figure. <m>\overrightarrow{GH} = \overrightarrow{HM}</m> since they have the same direction and 
                            equal length( use a ruler to check equality of length).
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ol>
            </p>
        </solution>
    </example>
